response:
We start by expressing the geometry problem in truns of vectors. Let \(\overrightarrow{A}\) and \(\overrightarrow{B}\) be the position vectors of points \(A\) and \(B,\) respectively. Let \(\overrightarrow{P}\) be the position vector of point \(P\). We are given that \(\overrightarrow{AP}:PB = 1:4,\) meaning that the distance from \(A\) to \(P\) is \(\frac{1}{5}\) of the total distance from \(A\) to \(B.\) Therefore, if \(\overrightarrow{P} = x\overrightarrow{A} + y\overrightarrow{B},\) then from the definition of vectors, we have
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{AP} &= \overrightarrow{P} - \overrightarrow{A} = \left(x\overrightarrow{A} + y\overrightarrow{B}\right) - \overrightarrow{A} = (x-1)\overrightarrow{A} + y\overvec{B}.
\end{align*}Since \(\overrightarrow{AP}:PB = 1:4\) and \(\overrightarrow{AP} + \overrightarrow{PB} = \overrightarrow{AB},\) we have
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{AP} &= \frac{1}{5}\overrightarrow{AB}. \end{align*}On the other hand, by the definition of point \(P,\)
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{PB} &= \frac{4}{5}\overrightarrow{AB}. \end{align*}We can interpret \(\overrightarrow{AB}\) as \(\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A},\) so we have
\begin{align*}
(x-1)\overrightarrow{A} + y\overrightarrow{B} &= \frac{1}{5}\left[\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A}\right]\\
(x+1)\overrightarrow{A} + (y-1)\overrightarrow{B} &= \vec{0}
\end{align*}Comparing the coefficients, we must have \(-x-1 = 0\) and \(y-1 = 0.\) From this, we get \((x,y) = \boxed{\left(-1,\frac{1}{5}\right)}.\)</answer>

