First, we need to find the angle between the radius and the chord. Since the angle at the center is $120^\circ$ (as it is subtended by the arc of the sector), the angle at the circumference (which is half of the central angle) will be $60^\circ$.
So the triangle formed by the radius and the word "chord" is an equilateral triangle of side 12.
Let $h$ be the distance from the center to the chord. So using the Pythagorean Theorem, we get
\begin{align*}
h^2+(6)^2&=12^2\\
h&=\sqrt{108}\\
&=6\sqrt{3}\\
\end{align*}
Since the chord length + limit distance + limit distance is equal to the circumference of the sector, we get the perimeter as
\begin{align*}
12+12(3)+6\sqrt{3}&=36+6\sqrt{3}\\
\end{align*}
<answer>$$ 36+6\sqrt{3} $$</answer>

